# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: contra-rotating-propellers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] 'Eaglet') is a Soviet *ekranoplan* that was designed by Rostislav Evgenievich Alexeyev of the Central Hydrofoil Design Bureau.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] The A-90 uses ground effect to fly a few meters above the surface.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] The Russians classify it as Ekranoplan Class B – it can achieve an altitude of 3,000 m (9,800 ft), placing it between Class A – which is limited to ground effect, and Class C, which exploits the ground effect only during take-offs and landings and otherwise functions as a typical airplane.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] The Soviet Navy command of the 1960s was very interested in a fast military transport capable of carrying a large payload.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] The Central Hydrofoil Design Bureau was one of the organizations working on this top-secret project, about which little was known until the fall of the Soviet Union.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] Alexeyev designed several prototypes in the 1960s.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] At the start of the 1970s, Alexeyev designed a medium-sized ekranoplan to be used as a military transport.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] The new vehicle was named *Orlyonok* ('Eaglet').
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] The first flying unit (S-21) was initially tested on the Volga River in the autumn of 1972, and the next year dismantled and transported to the Caspian Sea for continued testing.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] In 1975 the S-21 crashed during testing, later proved to be due to a deficiency in the alloy used for the hull.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] A different alloy was used in all subsequent units built.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] The *Orlyonok* was designed as a transport and a beach assault vehicle.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] Unlike other Soviet Ekranoplan designs, the *Orlyonok* was amphibious and was equipped with wheels for beaching and land based takeoffs.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] The layout of the engines on the *Orlyonok* was unusual and a testament of the special needs of such an unconventional aircraft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] Mounted in the top of the tail, it featured a massive Kuznetsov NK-12 turboprop, the most powerful turboprop ever made, which provided cruise power.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] The nose of the aircraft mounted two turbofan engines with the intakes on top of the nose and the exhaust along the side of the fuselage, the thrust of these engines being vectored under the wings to produce PAR thrust (increased lift and extra propulsion) for takeoff.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] Under cruise conditions and in ground effect, the front engines could be shut off since their power was unnecessary to keep the aircraft aloft; this also minimized intake of water, salt and low flying birds.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] Both takeoff and landing were assisted with large span-length flaps that greatly increased lift and could capture PAR thrust for increased air pressure.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] Water landings were assisted with a hydro-ski that extended out of the belly of the craft below the main wings.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] The front end of the *Orlyonok* was hinged behind the radome and the whole assembly could open sideways to speed disembarkation of the infantry it carried, or of a BTR armoured personnel carrier.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] The *Orlyonok* had a built in folding ramp that allowed it to load and unload vehicles with no external support.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] There were plans to resume production of the *Orlyonok*.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a-90-orlyonok] The craft were to have been built in Petrozavodsk.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a2j-super-savage] The **North American Aviation XA2J "Super Savage"** was a prototype carrier-based attack aircraft built in the early 1950s.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a2j-super-savage] It was developed by North American Aviation (NAA) from the smaller AJ Savage.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a2j-super-savage] The XA2J was intended to be a turboprop-powered derivative of the AJ Savage, with the design as initially proposed in December 1947 a simple modification of the Savage, with extensive use of components of the earlier aircraft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a2j-super-savage] The design gradually evolved, however, to improve performance and increase compatibility with operations from aircraft carriers, as it was recognized that the AJ Savage was deficient in performance and was a less-than-satisfactory carrier aircraft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a2j-super-savage] The A2J was essentially an enlarged AJ Savage with the two reciprocating engines replaced with two Allison T40 turboprop engines and removal of the tail-mounted turbojet.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a2j-super-savage] Like the AJ, it was a high-winged monoplane with unswept wings.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a2j-super-savage] The wings were fitted with leading edge slats and large trailing edge flaps, and folded outside of the engine nacelles to ease storage aboard ship.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a2j-super-savage] It had a crew of three: pilot, co-pilot/bombardier, and gunner who sat in a pressurised cabin in the nose of the aircraft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a2j-super-savage] Up to 10,500 lb (4,800 kg) of bombs could be carried in a large enclosed bomb-bay in the center fuselage, while the planned defensive armament was a remotely controlled tail turret with two 20 mm cannon.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a2j-super-savage] Construction of two prototypes started 1 October 1948, but due to delays developing the engines, the first flight was not until 4 January 1952.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a2j-super-savage] The competing Douglas XA3D, the prototypes of which were ordered the year after construction had begun on the XA2J prototypes, first flew in October 1952.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a2j-super-savage] The A3D had far superior performance, which doomed the XA2J.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a2j-super-savage] The root cause for the failure of the XA2J was the protracted development and poor reliability of the Allison T40 engines.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a2j-super-savage] The T40 engine was an ambitious engine design with two power sections, (the T38 was developed from the T40 to assist in its development, by using a single power section with extension shaft and gearbox), driving two large contra-rotating propellers through a combining gearbox.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a2j-super-savage] Both the engines and the gearbox proved to be unreliable.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a2j-super-savage] The T40 engine was also used in the developmental of other aircraft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/a2j-super-savage] After a number of engine-related mishaps, the XA2J project was abandoned and the second prototype was never flown.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Air-cooled engines are widely seen in applications where weight or simplicity is the primary goal.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity makes them suited for uses in small applications like chainsaws and lawn mowers, as well as small generators and similar roles.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] These qualities also make them highly suitable for aviation use, where they are widely used in general aviation aircraft and as auxiliary power units on larger aircraft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Their simplicity, in particular, also makes them common on motorcycles.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Most modern internal combustion engines are cooled by a closed circuit carrying liquid coolant through channels in the engine block and cylinder head.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] A fluid in these channels absorbs heat and then flows to a heat exchanger or radiator where the coolant releases heat into the air (or raw water, in the case of marine engines).
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Thus, while they are not *ultimately* cooled by the liquid, as the heat is exchanged with some other fluid like air, because of the liquid-coolant circuit they are known as *liquid-cooled*.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] In contrast, heat generated by an air-cooled engine is released directly into the air.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Typically this is facilitated with metal fins covering the outside of the cylinder head and cylinders which increase the surface area that air can act on.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Air may be force fed with the use of a fan and shroud to achieve efficient cooling with high volumes of air or simply by natural air flow with well designed and angled fins.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] In all combustion engines, a great percentage of the heat generated, around 44%, escapes through the exhaust.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Another 8% or so ends up in the oil, which itself has to be cooled in an oil cooler.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] This means less than half of the heat has to be removed through other systems.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] In an air-cooled engine, only about 12% of the heat flows out through the metal fins.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Air cooled engines usually run noisier, however it provides more simplicity which gives benefits when it comes to servicing and part replacement and is usually cheaper to be maintained.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Many motorcycles use air cooling for the sake of reducing weight and complexity.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Few current production automobiles have air-cooled engines (such as Tatra 815), but historically it was common for many high-volume vehicles.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] The orientation of the engine cylinders is commonly found in either single-cylinder or coupled in groups of two, and cylinders are commonly oriented in a horizontal fashion as a flat engine, while vertical straight-four engine have been used.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] During the 1920s and 30s there was a great debate in the aviation industry about the merits of air-cooled vs. liquid-cooled designs.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] At the beginning of this period, the liquid used for cooling was water at ambient pressure.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] The amount of heat carried away by a fluid is a function of its capacity and the difference in input and output temperatures.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] As the boiling point of water is reduced with lower pressure, and the water could not be efficiently pumped as steam, radiators had to have enough cooling power to account for the loss in cooling power as the aircraft climbed.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] The resulting radiators were quite large and caused a significant amount of aerodynamic drag.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] This placed the two designs roughly equal in terms of power to drag, but the air-cooled designs were almost always lighter and simpler.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] In 1921, the US Navy, largely due to the efforts of Commander Bruce G.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Leighton, decided that the simplicity of the air-cooled design would result in less maintenance workload, which was paramount given the limited working area of aircraft carriers.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Leighton's efforts led to the Navy underwriting air-cooled engine development at Pratt & Whitney and Wright Aeronautical.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Most other groups, especially in Europe where aircraft performance was rapidly improving, were more concerned with the issue of drag.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] While air-cooled designs were common on light aircraft and trainers, as well as some transport aircraft and bombers, liquid-cooled designs remained much more common for fighters and high-performance bombers.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] The drag issue was upset by the 1929 introduction of the NACA cowl, which greatly reduced the drag of air-cooled engines in spite of their larger frontal area, and the drag related to cooling was at this point largely even.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] This also led to development work attempting to eliminate the radiator entirely using evaporative cooling, allowing it to turn to steam and running the steam through tubes located just under the skin of the wings and fuselage, where the fast moving outside air condensed it back to water.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] While this concept was used on a number of record-setting aircraft in the late 1930s, it always proved impractical for production aircraft for a wide variety of reasons.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] In 1929, Curtiss began experiments replacing water with ethylene glycol in a Curtiss D-12 engine.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Ethylene glycol could run up to 250°C and reduced the radiator size by 50% compared to water-cooled designs.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] The experiments were extremely successful and by 1932 the company had switched all future designs to this coolant.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] At the time, Union Carbide held a monopoly on the industrial process to make ethylene glycol, so it was initially used only in the US, with Allison Engines picking it up soon after.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] It was not until the mid-1930s that Rolls-Royce adopted it as supplies improved, converting all of their engines to ethylene glycol.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] With the much smaller radiators and less fluid in the system, the weight and drag of these designs was well below contemporary air-cooled designs.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] On a weight basis, these liquid-cooled designs offered as much as 30% better performance.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] In the late- and post-war era, the high-performance field quickly moved to jet engines.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] This took away the primary market for late-model liquid-cooled engines.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Those roles that remained with piston power were mostly slower designs and civilian aircraft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] In these roles, the simplicity and reduction in servicing needs is far more important than drag, and from the end of the war on almost all piston aviation engines have been air-cooled, with few exceptions.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] As of 2020, most of the engines manufactured by Lycoming and Continental are used by major manufacturers of light aircraft Cirrus, Cessna and so on.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Other engine manufactures using air-cooled engine technology are ULPower and Jabiru, more active in the Light-Sport Aircraft (LSA) and ultralight aircraft market.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Rotax uses a combination of air-cooled cylinders and liquid-cooled cylinder heads.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Some small diesel engines, e.g. those made by Deutz AG and Lister Petter are air-cooled.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Probably the only big Euro 5 truck air-cooled engine (V8 320 kW power 2100 N·m torque one) is being produced by Tatra.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] BOMAG part of the FAYAT group also utilizes an air cooled inline 6 cylinder motor, in many of their construction vehicles.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Stationary or portable engines were commercially introduced early in the 1900s.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] The first commercial production was by the New Way Motor Company of Lansing, Michigan, US.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] The company produced air-cooled engines in single and twin cylinders in both horizontal and vertical cylinder format.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Subsequent to their initial production which was exported worldwide, other companies took up the advantages of this cooling method, especially in small portable engines.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-cooled-engine] Applications include mowers, generators, outboard motors, pump sets, saw benches and auxiliary power plants and more.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] An **air-start system** is a power source used to provide the initial rotation to start large diesel engines and gas turbines.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Compared to a gasoline (petrol) engine, a diesel engine has a very high compression ratio, an essential design feature, as it is the heat of compression that ignites the fuel.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] An electric starter with sufficient power to turn a large diesel engine would itself be so large as to be impractical so there is a need for an alternative system.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] An air start system has three main components along with various safety components, namely the air start injector, the distributor and the air receivers.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] When the system is initiated, starting air from the receivers is distributed by the distributor unit to each respective air start valve according to the firing order of the engine’s cylinders.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Safety components include flame traps, to prevent air line explosions, a turning gear interlock which ensures that air-start cannot be initiated when the turning gear is engaged, relief valves and isolation valves, as well as drain valves at certain points along the system.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Control components include the control valves and remote air-start valves.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] A direct start system as used on a marine slow-speed diesel is required to have up to 12 starts on a non-reversing engine or 6 starts on a reversible, or geared, engine.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] When starting the engine, compressed air is admitted to whichever cylinder has a piston just over top dead center, forcing it downward.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] As the engine starts to turn, the air-start valve on the next cylinder in line opens to continue the rotation.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] After several rotations, fuel is injected into the cylinders, the engine starts running and the air is cut off.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] To further complicate matters, a large engine is usually "blown over" first with zero fuel settings and the indicator cocks open, to prove that the engine is clear of any water build up and that everything is free to turn.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] After a successful blow ahead and a blow astern, the indicator cocks are closed on all the cylinders, and then the engine can be started on fuel.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Significant complexity is added to the engine by using an air-start system, as the cylinder head must have an extra valve in each cylinder to admit the air in for starting, plus the required control systems.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] This added complexity and cost limits the use of air-starters to very large and expensive reciprocating engines.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Another method of air-starting an internal combustion engine is by using compressed air or gas to drive a fluid motor in place of an electric motor.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] They can be used to start engines from 5 to 320 liters in size and if more starting power is necessary two or more motors can be used.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Starters of this type are used in place of electric motors because of their lighter weight and higher reliability.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] They can also outlast an electric starter by a factor of three and are easier to rebuild.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Engines operating in underground mining activities tend to operate on this type of starter system to reduce the risk of an electrical system igniting flammable material.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] All vane type air starters should have a lubricator installed to insure long-life and maximum performance.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Lubricators give the moving parts a needed friction barrier, reduce metal corrosion and keep vanes sealed properly against the cylinder walls.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Even the so-called lube-free air starters require lubrication to prolong trouble free life.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Two basic lubricator devices are typically employed.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] One is an in-line or reservoir type that typically stores up to 2 quarts of lubricant, and is installed along the air supply line.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] The second style of lubricator is a small one shot device that dispenses a measured amount of lubricant every time the starter is engaged.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Installed directly onto the air inlet of the starter, the in-line lubricators are self priming pneumatic pumps that require a 1/4″ lubrication line piped from as far away as 4 feet.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Air Starter lubricators perform best using misting type, non-detergent oils such as diesel fuel or Marvel Mystery oil.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] If emissions are a concern, there are environmentally friendly type lubricants available on the market.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Not all air starters require lubrication.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Turbine type air starters do not require air motor lubrication, although some turbine air starters do use an oil filled transmission that may require periodic inspections and maintenance.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Compressed air has been used to start gas turbine engines using air impingement starting (in which air is directed at the engine turbine blades through nozzles in the turbine casing, used on US Navy General Electric J79 engines).
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] It is much more efficient to use an air turbine starter (ATS) which is usually mounted on an accessory gearbox.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] An early axial compressor turbojet had an ATS located in the compressor nose cone (eg particular variants of the J79).
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Air impingement starting was not used for US military aircraft after the F-4B, A-5A and F-5 as the pneumatic energy requirement was several times greater than when using an air turbine starter.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] The gas turbine compressor required to start a J79 with impingement starting was sufficient to start two J79 engines simultaneously in a B-58 when using air turbine starters.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] An ATS has its own turbine and gears to change its low torque and high speed to low speed and high torque at the engine mounting pad.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Further gears in the engine gearbox connect to the engine shaft (high pressure spool on multi-spool engines).
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] Compared with electric starters, air-starters have a higher power-to-weight ratio so are used on large engines as an electric starter would be too big and, with its cables, too heavy and expensive.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] However, for smaller engines, which don't need as much starter power, an electric starter is more suitable.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-start-system] It has a dual function as a generator (is known as a starter/generator) at speeds above which the engine no longer requires starter assistance.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The **air turborocket** is a form of combined-cycle jet engine.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The basic layout includes a gas generator, which produces high pressure gas, that drives a turbine/compressor assembly which compresses atmospheric air into a combustion chamber.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] This mixture is then combusted before leaving the device through a nozzle and creating thrust.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] There are many different types of air turborockets.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The various types generally differ in how the gas generator section of the engine functions.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] Air turborockets are often referred to as **turboramjets**, **turboramjet rockets**, **turborocket expanders**, and many others.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] As there is no consensus on which names apply to which specific concepts, various sources may use the same name for two different concepts.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The benefit of this setup is increased specific impulse over that of a rocket.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] For the same carried mass of propellant as a rocket motor, the overall output of the air turborocket is much higher.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] In addition, it provides thrust throughout a much wider speed range than a ramjet, yet is much cheaper and easier to control than a gas turbine engine.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The air turborocket fills a niche (in terms of cost, reliability, ruggedness, and duration of thrust) between the solid-fuel rocket motor and gas turbine engine for missile applications.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] A **turborocket** is a type of aircraft engine combining elements of a jet engine and a rocket.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] It typically comprises a multi-stage fan driven by a turbine, which is driven by the hot gases exhausting from a series of small rocket-like motors mounted around the turbine inlet.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust gases mix with the fan discharge air, and combust with the air from the compressor before exhausting through a convergent-divergent propelling nozzle.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] Once a jet engine goes high enough in an atmosphere, there is insufficient oxygen to burn the jet fuel.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The idea behind a turborocket is to supplement the atmospheric oxygen with an onboard supply.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] This allows operation at a much higher altitude than a normal engine would allow.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The turborocket design offers a mixture of benefits with drawbacks.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] It is not a true rocket, so it cannot operate in space.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] Cooling the engine is not a problem because the burner and its hot exhaust gases are located behind the turbine blades.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The air turboramjet engine is a combined cycle engine that merges aspects of turbojet and ramjet engines.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The turboramjet is a hybrid engine that essentially consists of a turbojet mounted inside a ramjet.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The turbojet core is mounted inside a duct that contains a combustion chamber downstream of the turbojet nozzle.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The turboramjet can be run in turbojet mode at takeoff and during low-speed flight but then switch to ramjet mode to accelerate to high Mach numbers.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The operation of the engine is controlled using bypass flaps located just downstream of the diffuser.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] During low-speed flight, controllable flaps close the bypass duct and force air directly into the compressor section of the turbojet.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] During high-speed flight, the flaps block the flow into the turbojet, and the engine operates like a ramjet using the *aft* combustion chamber to produce thrust.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The engine would start out operating as a turbojet during takeoff and while climbing to altitude.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] Upon reaching high subsonic speed, the portion of the engine downstream of the turbojet would be used as an afterburner to accelerate the plane above the speed of sound.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] At lower speeds, air passes through an inlet and is then compressed by an axial compressor.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] That compressor is driven by a turbine, which is powered by hot, high-pressure gas from a combustion chamber.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] These initial aspects are very similar to how a turbojet operates, however, there are several differences.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The first is that the combustor in the turboramjet is often separate from the main airflow.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] Instead of combining air from the compressor with fuel to combust, the turboramjet combustor may use hydrogen and oxygen, carried on the aircraft, as its fuel for the combustor.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The air compressed by the compressor bypasses the combustor and turbine section of the engine, where it is mixed with the turbine exhaust.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust can be designed to be fuel-rich (i.e., the combustor does not burn all the fuel) which, when mixed with the compressed air, creates a hot fuel-air mixture which is ready to burn again.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] More fuel is injected into this air where it is again combusted.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The exhaust is ejected through a propelling nozzle, generating thrust.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] Picture shown lacks required bypass ducting around the compressor for ramjet operation.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] Shown is a low bypass turbojet with re-heat.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] The turboramjet engine is used when space is constrained, as it takes up less space than separate ramjet and turbojet engines.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] Since a ramjet must already be traveling at high speeds before it will start working, a ramjet-powered aircraft is incapable of taking off from a runway under its own power; that is the advantage of the turbojet, which is a member of the gas turbine family of engines.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] A turbojet does not rely purely on the motion of the engine to compress the incoming air flow; instead, the turbojet contains some additional rotating machinery that compresses incoming air and allows the engine to function during takeoff and at slow speeds.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] In applications which stay relatively in the atmosphere and require longer durations of lower thrust over a specific speed range the air turborocket can have a weight advantage over the standard solid fuel rocket motor.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/air-turborocket] In terms of volumetric requirements, the rocket motor has the advantage due to the lack of inlet ducts and other air management devices.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] Aircraft equipped with **contra-rotating propellers** (**CRP**), **coaxial contra-rotating propellers**, or **high-speed propellers**, apply the maximum power of usually a single engine piston powered or turboprop engine to drive a pair of coaxial propellers in contra-rotation.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] Two propellers are arranged one behind the other, and power is transferred from the engine via a planetary gear or spur gear transmission.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] Although contra-rotating propellers are also known as *counter-rotating propellers*, the term is much more widely used when referring to airscrews on separate non-coaxial shafts turning in opposite directions.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] When airspeed is low, the mass of the air flowing through the propeller disk (thrust) causes a significant amount of tangential or rotational air flow to be created by the spinning blades.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The energy of this tangential air flow is wasted in a single-propeller design, and causes handling problems at low speed as the air strikes the vertical stabilizer, causing the aircraft to yaw left or right, depending on the direction of propeller rotation.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] To use this wasted effort, the placement of a second propeller behind the first takes advantage of the disturbed airflow.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] A well designed contra-rotating propeller will have no rotational air flow, pushing a maximum amount of air uniformly through the propeller disk, resulting in high performance and low induced energy loss.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] It also serves to counter the asymmetrical torque effect of a conventional propeller (see P-factor).
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] Some contra-rotating systems were designed to be used at takeoff for maximum power and efficiency under such conditions, and allowing one of the propellers to be disabled during cruise to extend flight time.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The torque on the aircraft from a pair of contra-rotating propellers effectively cancels out.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] Contra-rotating propellers have been found to be between 6% and 16% more efficient than normal propellers.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] However they can be very noisy, with increases in noise in the axial (forward and aft) direction of up to 30 dB, and tangentially 10 dB.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] Most of this extra noise can be found in the higher frequencies.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] These substantial noise problems limit commercial applications.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] One possibility is to enclose the contra-rotating propellers in a shroud.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] It is also helpful if the tip speed or the loading of the blades is reduced, if the aft propeller has fewer blades or a smaller diameter than the fore propeller, or if the spacing between the aft and fore propellers is increased.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The efficiency of a contra-rotating propeller is somewhat offset by its mechanical complexity and the added weight of this gearing that makes the aircraft heavier, thus some performance is sacrificed to carry it.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] Nonetheless, coaxial contra-rotating propellers and rotors have been used in several military aircraft, such as the Tupolev Tu-95 "Bear".
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] They are also being examined for use in airliners.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] While several nations experimented with contra-rotating propellers in aircraft, only the United Kingdom and Soviet Union produced them in large numbers.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The first aircraft to be fitted with a contra-rotating propeller to fly was in the US when two inventors from Ft Worth, Texas tested the concept on an aircraft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] A contra-rotating propeller was patented by F.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] Some of the more successful British aircraft with contra-rotating propellers are the Avro Shackleton, powered by the Rolls-Royce Griffon engine, and the Fairey Gannet, which used the Double Mamba Mk.101 engine.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] In the Double Mamba two separate power sections drove one propeller each, allowing one power section (engine) to be shut down in flight, increasing endurance.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] Another naval aircraft, the Westland Wyvern had contra-rotating propellers.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The Martin-Baker MB 5 test aircraft also used this propeller type.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] Later variants of the Seafire used the Griffon with contra-rotating props, after testing of the configuration had been undertaken on a Supermarine Spitfire.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] In the Spitfire/Seafire and Shackleton's case the primary reason for using contra-rotating propellers was to increase the propeller blade-area, and hence absorb greater engine power, within a propeller diameter limited by the height of the aircraft's undercarriage.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The Short Sturgeon used two Merlin 140s with contra-rotating propellers.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The Bristol Brabazon prototype airliner used eight Bristol Centaurus engines driving four pairs of contra-rotating propellers, each engine driving a single propeller.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The post-war SARO Princess prototype flying boat airliner also had eight of its ten engines driving contra-rotating propellers.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] In the 1950s, the Soviet Union's Kuznetsov Design Bureau developed the NK-12 turboprop.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] It drives an eight-blade contra-rotating propeller and, at 15,000 shaft horsepower (11,000 kilowatts), it is the most powerful turboprop in service.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] Four NK-12 engines power the Tupolev Tu-95 *Bear*, the only turboprop bomber to enter service, as well as one of the fastest propeller-driven aircraft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The Tu-114, an airliner derivative of the Tu-95, holds the world speed record for propeller aircraft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The Tu-95 was also the first Soviet bomber to have intercontinental range.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The Tu-126 AEW aircraft and Tu-142 maritime patrol aircraft are two more NK-12 powered designs derived from the Tu-95.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The NK-12 engine powers another well-known Soviet aircraft, the Antonov An-22 Antheus, a heavy-lift cargo aircraft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] At the time of its introduction, the An-22 was the largest aircraft in the world and is still, by far, the world's largest turboprop-powered aircraft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] From the 1960s through the 1970s, it set several world records in the categories of maximum payload-to-height ratio and maximum payload lifted to altitude.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] Of lesser note is the use of the NK-12 engine in the A-90 Orlyonok, a mid-size Soviet ekranoplan.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The A-90 uses one NK-12 engine mounted at the top of its T-tail, along with two turbofans installed in the nose.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] In the 1980s, Kuznetsov continued to develop powerful contra-rotating engines.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The NK-110, which was tested in the late 1980s, had a contra-rotating propeller configuration with four blades in front and four in back, like the NK-12.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] Its 190-inch propeller diameter (4.7-metre) was smaller than the NK-12's 220–240 in (5.6–6.2 m) diameter, but it produced a power output of 21,007 hp (15,665 kW), delivering a takeoff thrust of 40,000 pounds-force (177 kilonewtons).
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] Even more powerful was the NK-62, which was in development throughout most of the decade.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The NK-62 had an identical propeller diameter and blade configuration to the NK-110, but it offered a higher takeoff thrust of 55,000 lbf (245 kN).
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The associated NK-62M had a takeoff thrust of 64,100 lbf (285.2 kN), and it could deliver 70,700 lbf (314.7 kN) of emergency thrust.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] Unlike the NK-12, however, these later engines were not adopted by any of the aircraft design bureaus.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] In 1994, Antonov produced the An-70, a heavy transport aircraft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] It is powered by four Progress D-27 propfan engines driving contra-rotating propellers.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The characteristics of the D-27 engine and its propeller make it a propfan, a hybrid between a turbofan engine and a turboprop engine.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The Convair R3Y Tradewind flying boat entered service with contra-rotating propellers.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] However, both piston-engined and turboprop-powered propeller-driven aircraft were reaching their zenith and new technological developments such as the advent of the pure turbojet and turbofan engines, both without propellers, meant that the designs were quickly eclipsed.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The US propeller manufacturer, Hamilton Standard, bought a Fairey Gannet in 1983 to study the effects of counter rotation on propeller noise and blade vibratory stresses.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The Gannet was particularly suitable because the independently-driven propellers provided a comparison between counter and single rotation.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] An Austrian company, Sun Flightcraft, distributes a contra-rotating gearbox for use on Rotax 503 and 582 engines on ultralight and microlight aircraft.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The Coax-P was developed by Hans Neudorfer of NeuraJet and allows powered hang-gliders and parachutes to develop 15 to 20 percent more power while reducing torque moments.
[src:contra-rotating-propellers/contra-rotating-propellers] The manufacturer also reports reduced noise levels from dual contra-rotating props using the Coax-P gearbox.
